66756,-0.065029,-0.00570936,0.02755388,0.15247464,-0.00277317,0.05536851,-0.00596781,0.03241944,0.00792137,-0.00102482,-0.00618161,0.00804301,0.065432,0.09440879,-0.04068136,0.02586871,0.0520144,-0.07785925,0.05910232,0.04356898,-0.00933987,0.0253127,0.04677382,0.02347118,-0.01581541,0.08657465,-0.0902633,-0.00715312,-0.04711821,0.01632904,0.00839945,0.02260844,0.04659825,0.08168546,0.01867573,0.02453734,-0.0114964,0.02114813,-0.03841632,0.03674185,-0.02232968,0.03741349,0.02950031,-0.02602787,0.13286647,0.00680308],"last_embed":{"hash":"i1jyqf","tokens":450}}},"last_read":{"hash":"i1jyqf","at":1774951890800},"class_name":"SmartSource","last_import":{"mtime":1774951821709,"size":3781,"at":1774951884804,"hash":"i1jyqf"},"blocks":{"#---frontmatter---":[1,89],"#Electrical stimulation alleviates depressive-like behaviors of rats: investigation of brain targets and potential mechanisms":[91,95],"#Electrical stimulation alleviates depressive-like behaviors of rats: investigation of brain targets and potential mechanisms#{1}":[93,95]},"outlinks":[{"title":"Author/Lee Wei Lim","target":"Author/Lee Wei Lim","line":69},{"title":"Author/Lee Wei Lim","target":"Author/Lee Wei Lim","line":70},{"title":"Author/Jos Prickaerts","target":"Author/Jos Prickaerts","line":71},{"title":"Author/Jos Prickaerts","target":"Author/Jos Prickaerts","line":72},{"title":"Author/Gemma Huguet","target":"Author/Gemma Huguet","line":73},{"title":"Author/Gemma Huguet","target":"Author/Gemma Huguet","line":74},{"title":"Author/Gemma Huguet","target":"Author/Gemma Huguet","line":75},{"title":"Author/Elisabet Kádár","target":"Author/Elisabet Kádár","line":76},{"title":"Author/Elisabet Kádár","target":"Author/Elisabet Kádár","line":77},{"title":"Author/E. Kádár","target":"Author/E. Kádár","line":78},{"title":"Author/Henrike Hartung","target":"Author/Henrike Hartung","line":79},{"title":"Author/Henrike Hartung","target":"Author/Henrike Hartung","line":80},{"title":"Author/Trevor Sharp","target":"Author/Trevor Sharp","line":81},{"title":"Author/Trevor Sharp","target":"Author/Trevor Sharp","line":82},{"title":"Author/Yasin Temel","target":"Author/Yasin Temel","line":83},{"title":"Author/Yasin Temel","target":"Author/Yasin Temel","line":84},{"title":"PDF","target":"biblib/lim_electrical_2015/lim_electrical_2015.pdf","line":86}],"metadata":{"id":"lim_electrical_2015","type":"article-journal","title":"Electrical stimulation alleviates depressive-like behaviors of rats: investigation of brain targets and potential mechanisms","issued":{"date-parts":[[2015]]},"DOI":"10.1038/tp.2015.24","container-title":"Translational Psychiatry","abstract":"Deep brain stimulation (DBS) is a promising therapy for patients with refractory depression. However, key questions remain with regard to which brain target(s) should be used for stimulation, and which mechanisms underlie the therapeutic effects. Here, we investigated the effect of DBS, with low- and high-frequency stimulation (LFS, HFS), in different brain regions (ventromedial prefrontal cortex, vmPFC; cingulate cortex, Cg; nucleus accumbens (NAc) core or shell; lateral habenula, LHb; and ventral tegmental area) on a variety of depressive-like behaviors using rat models. In the naive animal study, we found that HFS of the Cg, vmPFC, NAc core and LHb reduced anxiety levels and increased motivation for food. In the chronic unpredictable stress model, there was a robust depressive-like behavioral phenotype. Moreover, vmPFC HFS, in a comparison of all stimulated targets, produced the most profound antidepressant effects with enhanced hedonia, reduced anxiety and decreased forced-swim immobility. In the following set of electrophysiological and histochemical experiments designed to unravel some of the underlying mechanisms, we found that vmPFC HFS evoked a specific modulation of the serotonergic neurons in the dorsal raphe nucleus (DRN), which have long been linked to mood. Finally, using a neuronal mapping approach by means of c-Fos expression, we found that vmPFC HFS modulated a brain circuit linked to the DRN and known to be involved in affect. In conclusion, HFS of the vmPFC produced the most potent antidepressant effects in naive rats and rats subjected to stress by mechanisms also including the DRN.","tags":["#literature_note"],"author":[{"family":"Lim","given":"Lee Wei","literal":""},{"family":"Lim","given":"Lee Wei","literal":""},{"family":"Prickaerts","given":"Jos","literal":""},{"family":"Prickaerts","given":"Jos","literal":""},{"family":"Huguet","given":"Gemma","literal":""},{"family":"Huguet","given":"Gemma","literal":""},{"family":"Huguet","given":"Gemma","literal":""},{"family":"Kádár","given":"Elisabet","literal":""},{"family":"Kádár","given":"Elisabet","literal":""},{"family":"Kádár","given":"E.","literal":""},{"family":"Hartung","given":"Henrike","literal":""},{"family":"Hartung","given":"Henrike","literal":""},{"family":"Sharp","given":"Trevor","literal":""},{"family":"Sharp","given":"Trevor","literal":""},{"family":"Temel","given":"Yasin","literal":""},{"family":"Temel","given":"Yasin","literal":""}],"citation-key":"lim_electrical_2015","year":"2015","dateCreated":"2026-03-31","reading-status":"to-read","aliases":["Electrical stimulation alleviates depressive-like behaviors of rats: investigation of brain targets and potential mechanisms"],"author-links":["[[Author/Lee Wei Lim]]","[[Author/Lee Wei Lim]]","[[Author/Jos Prickaerts]]","[[Author/Jos Prickaerts]]","[[Author/Gemma Huguet]]","[[Author/Gemma Huguet]]","[[Author/Gemma Huguet]]","[[Author/Elisabet Kádár]]","[[Author/Elisabet Kádár]]","[[Author/E. Kádár]]","[[Author/Henrike Hartung]]","[[Author/Henrike Hartung]]","[[Author/Trevor Sharp]]","[[Author/Trevor Sharp]]","[[Author/Yasin Temel]]","[[Author/Yasin Temel]]"],"attachment":["[[biblib/lim_electrical_2015/lim_electrical_2015.pdf|PDF]]"],"related":[[]]},"task_lines":[],"tasks":{},"codeblock_ranges":[],"last_embed":{"hash":"i1jyqf","at":1774951890789}},"smart_blocks:Research/@